   3.681107598270144*^9}},
 Background->None,ExpressionUUID->"5ac1aff9-8393-495d-8735-90190c932ade"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The routines ",
 StyleBox["PolarizedDensityOperator",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["SingletPolarizedDensityOperator",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " set up ensemble density operators with arbitrary polarization levels. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.681107601049687*^9, 
  3.681107646837014*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"093a9b43-8080-4d20-b073-\
00e4ea001ea7"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["PolarizedDensityOperator",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.588074747297937*^9, 3.58807475427406*^9}, 
   3.681107655503767*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5fd7185a-a12d-4d09-a952-\
53e68dcbaf6b"],

Cell["\<\
PolarizedDensityOperator is used to set up a density operator with a \
specified degree of oriented spin angular momentum along an arbitrary axis. \
By default, the z-axis is chosen, and the default polarization level is 1. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.681107761915512*^9, 
  3.681107849166441*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8c489cb1-66ba-45ed-aaf9-\
5b48e0851a67"],

Cell["\<\
In the 3-spin example below, PolarizedDensityOperator[\[NonBreakingSpace]] \
generates a density operator with maximum polarization along the z-axis:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.681107761915512*^9, 
  3.681107903296574*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"df07e047-791b-4c54-81e5-\
10ca2608dfb3"],

